&lt;p&gt;A book I have recently read, &lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;&amp;lt;iframe src=&amp;quot;http://rcm.amazon.com/e/cm?lt1=_blank&amp;amp;bc1=000000&amp;amp;IS2=1&amp;amp;bg1=FFFFFF&amp;amp;fc1=000000&amp;amp;lc1=0000FF&amp;amp;t=warrspir-20&amp;amp;o=1&amp;amp;p=8&amp;amp;l=as1&amp;amp;m=amazon&amp;amp;f=ifr&amp;amp;md=10FE9736YVPPT7A0FBG2&amp;amp;asins=0762415339&amp;quot; style=&amp;quot;width:120px;height:240px;&amp;quot; scrolling=&amp;quot;no&amp;quot; marginwidth=&amp;quot;0&amp;quot; marginheight=&amp;quot;0&amp;quot; frameborder=&amp;quot;0&amp;quot;&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/iframe&amp;gt; &#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;No More Mr. Nice Guy&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/em&gt;by Dr. Robert A. Glover, adds to the growing conversation on masculinity in our society. Blogs like the &lt;a href=&#34;http://artofmanliness.com/&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;Art of Manliness&lt;/a&gt;, the renewed interest in old-school shaving, the death of the metrosexual (maybe? hopefully) are all part of the movement to reclaim what it means to be a real man. Gover&#39;s book is an important contribution to that movement because it addresses one of the biggest stumbling blocks that recovering pansies have to deal with: the misperception that being a Nice Guy will get you anywhere in life.</description>
